# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: coreboot
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:coreboot/bios] In computing, **BIOS** or the **Basic Input/Output System** is a type of firmware used to provide runtime services for operating systems and programs and to perform hardware initialization during the booting process (power-on startup).
[src:coreboot/bios] On a computer using BIOS firmware, the firmware comes pre-installed on the computer's motherboard.
[src:coreboot/bios] The name originates from the **B**asic **I**nput/**O**utput **S**ystem used in the CP/M operating system in 1975.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS firmware was originally proprietary to the IBM PC; it was reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:coreboot/bios] The interface of that original system serves as a *de facto* standard.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS in older PCs initializes and tests the system hardware components (power-on self-test or POST for short), and loads a boot loader from a mass storage device which then initializes a kernel.
[src:coreboot/bios] In the era of DOS, the BIOS provided BIOS interrupt calls for the keyboard, display, storage, and other input/output (I/O) devices that standardized an interface to application programs and the operating system.
[src:coreboot/bios] More recent operating systems do not use the BIOS interrupt calls after startup.
[src:coreboot/bios] Most BIOS implementations are specifically designed to work with a particular computer or motherboard model, by interfacing with various devices especially system chipset.
[src:coreboot/bios] Originally, BIOS firmware was stored in a ROM chip on the PC motherboard.
[src:coreboot/bios] In later computer systems, the BIOS contents are stored on flash memory so it can be rewritten without removing the chip from the motherboard.
[src:coreboot/bios] This allows easy, end-user updates to the BIOS firmware so new features can be added or bugs can be fixed, but it also creates a possibility for the computer to become infected with BIOS rootkits.
[src:coreboot/bios] Furthermore, a BIOS upgrade that fails could brick the motherboard.
[src:coreboot/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) is a successor to the legacy PC BIOS, aiming to address its technical limitations.
[src:coreboot/bios] UEFI firmware may include legacy BIOS compatibility to maintain compatibility with operating systems and option cards that do not support UEFI native operation.
[src:coreboot/bios] Intel phased out providing support for booting from the BIOS interface from 2020 to 2024 depending on the platform.
[src:coreboot/bios] The last version of Microsoft Windows to officially support running on PCs which use legacy BIOS firmware is Windows 10 as Windows 11 requires a UEFI-compliant system (except for IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11 since version 24H2).
[src:coreboot/bios] The term BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) was created by Gary Kildall and first appeared in the CP/M operating system in 1975, describing the machine-specific part of CP/M loaded during boot time that interfaces directly with the hardware.
[src:coreboot/bios] Versions of MS-DOS, PC DOS or DR-DOS contain a file called variously "IO.SYS", "IBMBIO.COM", "IBMBIO.SYS", or "DRBIOS.SYS"; this file is known as the "DOS BIOS" (also known as the "DOS I/O System") and contains the lower-level hardware-specific part of the operating system.
[src:coreboot/bios] Together with the underlying hardware-specific but operating system-independent "System BIOS", which resides in ROM, it represents the analogue to the "CP/M BIOS".
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS originally proprietary to the IBM PC has been reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:coreboot/bios] With the introduction of PS/2 machines, IBM divided the System BIOS into real- and protected-mode portions.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS of the original IBM PC and XT had no interactive user interface.
[src:coreboot/bios] Error codes or messages were displayed on the screen, or coded series of sounds were generated to signal errors when the power-on self-test (POST) had not proceeded to the point of successfully initializing a video display adapter.
[src:coreboot/bios] Options on the IBM PC and XT were set by switches and jumpers on the main board and on expansion cards.
[src:coreboot/bios] Starting around the mid-1990s, it became typical for the BIOS ROM to include a *"BIOS configuration utility"* (BCU) or "BIOS setup utility", accessed at system power-up by a particular key sequence.
[src:coreboot/bios] This program allowed the user to set system configuration options, of the type formerly set using DIP switches, through an interactive menu system controlled through the keyboard.
[src:coreboot/bios] In the interim period, IBM-compatible PCs‍—‌including the IBM AT‍—‌held configuration settings in battery-backed RAM and used a bootable configuration program on floppy disk, not in the ROM, to set the configuration options contained in this memory.
[src:coreboot/bios] The floppy disk was supplied with the computer, and if it was lost the system settings could not be changed.
[src:coreboot/bios] The same applied in general to computers with an EISA bus, for which the configuration program was called an EISA Configuration Utility (ECU).
[src:coreboot/bios] A modern Wintel-compatible computer provides a setup routine essentially unchanged in nature from the ROM-resident BIOS setup utilities of the late 1990s; the user can configure hardware options using the keyboard and video display.
[src:coreboot/bios] The modern Wintel machine may store the BIOS configuration settings in flash ROM, perhaps the same flash ROM that holds the BIOS itself.
[src:coreboot/bios] Peripheral cards such as hard disk drive host bus adapters and video cards have their own firmware, and BIOS extension option ROM code may be a part of the expansion card firmware; that code provides additional capabilities in the BIOS.
[src:coreboot/bios] Code in option ROMs runs before the BIOS boots the operating system from mass storage.
[src:coreboot/bios] These ROMs typically test and initialize hardware, add new BIOS services, or replace existing BIOS services with their own services.
[src:coreboot/bios] For example, a SCSI controller usually has a BIOS extension ROM that adds support for hard drives connected through that controller.
[src:coreboot/bios] An extension ROM could in principle contain operating system, or it could implement an entirely different boot process such as network booting.
[src:coreboot/bios] Operation of an IBM-compatible computer system can be completely changed by removing or inserting an adapter card (or a ROM chip) that contains a BIOS extension ROM.
[src:coreboot/bios] The motherboard BIOS typically contains code for initializing and bootstrapping integrated display and integrated storage.
[src:coreboot/bios] In addition, plug-in adapter cards such as SCSI, RAID, network interface cards, and video cards often include their own BIOS (e.g., Video BIOS), complementing or replacing the system BIOS code for the given component.
[src:coreboot/bios] Even devices built into the motherboard can behave in this way; their option ROMs can be a part of the motherboard BIOS.
[src:coreboot/bios] An add-in card requires an option ROM if the card is not supported by the motherboard BIOS and the card needs to be initialized or made accessible through BIOS services before the operating system can be loaded (usually this means it is required in the boot process).
[src:coreboot/bios] An additional advantage of ROM on some early PC systems (notably including the IBM PCjr) was that ROM was faster than main system RAM.
[src:coreboot/bios] Option ROMs normally reside on adapter cards.
[src:coreboot/bios] The IBM PCjr is unique among PCs in having two ROM cartridge slots on the front.
[src:coreboot/bios] Cartridges in these slots map into the same region of the upper memory area used for option ROMs, and the cartridges can contain option ROM modules that the BIOS would recognize.
[src:coreboot/bios] The cartridges can also contain other types of ROM modules, such as BASIC programs, that are handled differently.
[src:coreboot/bios] One PCjr cartridge can contain several ROM modules of different types, possibly stored together in one ROM chip.
[src:coreboot/bios] The 8086 and 8088 start at physical address FFFF0h.
[src:coreboot/bios] The 80286 starts at physical address FFFFF0h.
[src:coreboot/bios] The 80386 and later x86 processors start at physical address FFFFFFF0h.
[src:coreboot/bios] When the system is initialized, the first instruction of the BIOS appears at that address.
[src:coreboot/bios] If the system has just been powered up or the reset button was pressed ("cold boot"), the full power-on self-test (POST) is run.
[src:coreboot/bios] If Ctrl+Alt+Delete was pressed ("warm boot"), a special flag value stored in nonvolatile BIOS memory ("CMOS") tested by the BIOS allows bypass of the lengthy POST and memory detection.
[src:coreboot/bios] The POST identifies, tests and initializes system devices such as the CPU, chipset, RAM, motherboard, video card, keyboard, mouse, hard disk drive, optical disc drive and other hardware, including integrated peripherals.
[src:coreboot/bios] Early IBM PCs had a routine in the POST that would download a program into RAM through the keyboard port and run it.
[src:coreboot/bios] This feature was intended for factory test or diagnostic purposes.
[src:coreboot/bios] After the motherboard BIOS completes its POST, most BIOS versions search for option ROM modules, also called BIOS extension ROMs, and execute them.
[src:coreboot/bios] The motherboard BIOS scans for extension ROMs in a portion of the "upper memory area" (the part of the x86 real-mode address space at and above address 0xA0000) and runs each ROM found, in order.
[src:coreboot/bios] To discover memory-mapped option ROMs, a BIOS implementation scans the real-mode address space from `0x0C0000` to `0x0F0000` on 2 KB (2,048 bytes) boundaries, looking for a two-byte ROM *signature*: 0x55 followed by 0xAA.
[src:coreboot/bios] In a valid expansion ROM, this signature is followed by a single byte indicating the number of 512-byte blocks the expansion ROM occupies in real memory, and the next byte is the option ROM's entry point (also known as its "entry offset").
[src:coreboot/bios] If the ROM has a valid checksum, the BIOS transfers control to the entry address, which in a normal BIOS extension ROM should be the beginning of the extension's initialization routine.
[src:coreboot/bios] At this point, the extension ROM code takes over, typically testing and initializing the hardware it controls and registering interrupt vectors for use by post-boot applications.
[src:coreboot/bios] It may use BIOS services (including those provided by previously initialized option ROMs) to provide a user configuration interface, to display diagnostic information, or to do anything else that it requires.
[src:coreboot/bios] An option ROM should normally return to the BIOS after completing its initialization process.
[src:coreboot/bios] Once (and if) an option ROM returns, the BIOS continues searching for more option ROMs, calling each as it is found, until the entire option ROM area in the memory space has been scanned.
[src:coreboot/bios] It is possible that an option ROM will not return to BIOS, pre-empting the BIOS's boot sequence altogether.
[src:coreboot/bios] After the POST completes and, in a BIOS that supports option ROMs, after the option ROM scan is completed and all detected ROM modules with valid checksums have been called, the BIOS calls interrupt 19h to start boot processing.
[src:coreboot/bios] Post-boot, programs loaded can also call interrupt 19h to reboot the system, but they must be careful to disable interrupts and other asynchronous hardware processes that may interfere with the BIOS rebooting process, or else the system may hang or crash while it is rebooting.
[src:coreboot/bios] When interrupt 19h is called, the BIOS attempts to locate boot loader software on a "boot device", such as a hard disk, a floppy disk, CD, or DVD.
[src:coreboot/bios] It loads and executes the first boot software it finds, giving it control of the PC.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS uses the boot devices set in Nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS), or, in the earliest PCs, DIP switches.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS checks each device in order to see if it is bootable by attempting to load the first sector (boot sector).
[src:coreboot/bios] If the sector cannot be read, the BIOS proceeds to the next device.
[src:coreboot/bios] If the sector is read successfully, some BIOSes will also check for the boot sector signature 0x55 0xAA in the last two bytes of the sector (which is 512 bytes long), before accepting a boot sector and considering the device bootable.
[src:coreboot/bios] When a bootable device is found, the BIOS transfers control to the loaded sector.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS does not interpret the contents of the boot sector other than to possibly check for the boot sector signature in the last two bytes.
[src:coreboot/bios] Interpretation of data structures like partition tables and BIOS Parameter Blocks is done by the boot program in the boot sector itself or by other programs loaded through the boot process.
[src:coreboot/bios] A non-disk device such as a network adapter attempts booting by a procedure that is defined by its option ROM or the equivalent integrated into the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:coreboot/bios] As such, option ROMs may also influence or supplant the boot process defined by the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:coreboot/bios] With the El Torito optical media boot standard, the optical drive actually emulates a 3.5" high-density floppy disk to the BIOS for boot purposes.
[src:coreboot/bios] Reading the "first sector" of a CD-ROM or DVD-ROM is not a simply defined operation like it is on a floppy disk or a hard disk.
[src:coreboot/bios] Furthermore, the complexity of the medium makes it difficult to write a useful boot program in one sector.
[src:coreboot/bios] The bootable virtual floppy disk can contain software that provides access to the optical medium in its native format.
[src:coreboot/bios] If an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots (such as from a network device or a SCSI adapter) in a cooperative way, it can use the *BIOS Boot Specification* (BBS) API to register its ability to do so.
[src:coreboot/bios] Once the expansion ROMs have registered using the BBS APIs, the user can select among the available boot options from within the BIOS's user interface.
[src:coreboot/bios] This is why most BBS compliant PC BIOS implementations will not allow the user to enter the BIOS's user interface until the expansion ROMs have finished executing and registering themselves with the BBS API.
[src:coreboot/bios] Also, if an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots unilaterally, it can simply hook interrupt 19h or other interrupts normally called from interrupt 19h, such as interrupt 13h, the BIOS disk service, to intercept the BIOS boot process.
[src:coreboot/bios] Then it can replace the BIOS boot process with one of its own, or it can merely modify the boot sequence by inserting its own boot actions into it, by preventing the BIOS from detecting certain devices as bootable, or both.
[src:coreboot/bios] Before the BIOS Boot Specification was promulgated, this was the only way for expansion ROMs to implement boot capability for devices not supported for booting by the native BIOS of the motherboard.
[src:coreboot/bios] The user can select the boot priority implemented by the BIOS.
[src:coreboot/bios] For example, most computers have a hard disk that is bootable, but sometimes there is a removable-media drive that has higher boot priority, so the user can cause a removable disk to be booted.
[src:coreboot/bios] In most modern BIOSes, the boot priority order can be configured by the user.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS in an early PC also usually would only boot from the first floppy disk drive or the first hard disk drive, even if there were two drives installed.
[src:coreboot/bios] On the original IBM PC and XT, if no bootable disk was found, the BIOS would try to start ROM BASIC with the interrupt call to interrupt 18h.
[src:coreboot/bios] Since few programs used BASIC in ROM, clone PC makers left it out; then a computer that failed to boot from a disk would display "No ROM BASIC" and halt (in response to interrupt 18h).
[src:coreboot/bios] Later computers would display a message like "No bootable disk found"; some would prompt for a disk to be inserted and a key to be pressed to retry the boot process.
[src:coreboot/bios] A modern BIOS may display nothing or may automatically enter the BIOS configuration utility when the boot process fails.
[src:coreboot/bios] The environment for the boot program is very simple: the CPU is in real mode and the general-purpose and segment registers are undefined, except SS, SP, CS, and DL.
[src:coreboot/bios] CS:IP always points to physical address `0x07C00`.
[src:coreboot/bios] What values CS and IP actually have is not well defined.
[src:coreboot/bios] Because boot programs are always loaded at this fixed address, there is no need for a boot program to be relocatable.
[src:coreboot/bios] DL may contain the drive number, as used with interrupt 13h, of the boot device.
[src:coreboot/bios] SS:SP points to a valid stack that is presumably large enough to support hardware interrupts, but otherwise SS and SP are undefined.
[src:coreboot/bios] (A stack must be already set up in order for interrupts to be serviced, and interrupts must be enabled in order for the system timer-tick interrupt, which BIOS always uses at least to maintain the time-of-day count and which it initializes during POST, to be active and for the keyboard to work.
[src:coreboot/bios] At boot time, all BIOS services are available, and the memory below address `0x00400` contains the interrupt vector table.
[src:coreboot/bios] BIOS POST has initialized the system timers, interrupt controller(s), DMA controller(s), and other motherboard/chipset hardware as necessary to bring all BIOS services to ready status.
[src:coreboot/bios] DRAM refresh for all system DRAM in conventional memory and extended memory, but not necessarily expanded memory, has been set up and is running.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS maintains a reserved block of system RAM at addresses `0x00400–0x004FF` with various parameters initialized during the POST.
[src:coreboot/bios] All memory at and above address `0x00500` can be used by the boot program; it may even overwrite itself.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS ROM is customized to the particular manufacturer's hardware, allowing low-level services (such as reading a keystroke or writing a sector of data to diskette) to be provided in a standardized way to programs, including operating systems.
[src:coreboot/bios] For example, an IBM PC might have either a monochrome or a color display adapter (using different display memory addresses and hardware), but a single, standard, BIOS system call may be invoked to display a character at a specified position on the screen in text mode or graphics mode.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS provides a small library of basic input/output functions to operate peripherals (such as the keyboard, rudimentary text and graphics display functions and so forth).
[src:coreboot/bios] Operating systems and executive software that are designed to supersede this basic firmware functionality provide replacement software interfaces to application software.
[src:coreboot/bios] Applications can also provide these services to themselves.
[src:coreboot/bios] This began even in the 1980s under MS-DOS, when programmers observed that using the BIOS video services for graphics display were very slow.
[src:coreboot/bios] To increase the speed of screen output, many programs bypassed the BIOS and programmed the video display hardware directly.
[src:coreboot/bios] Other graphics programmers, particularly but not exclusively in the demoscene, observed that there were technical capabilities of the PC display adapters that were not supported by the IBM BIOS and could not be taken advantage of without circumventing it.
[src:coreboot/bios] Since the AT-compatible BIOS ran in Intel real mode, operating systems that ran in protected mode on 286 and later processors required hardware device drivers compatible with protected mode operation to replace BIOS services.
[src:coreboot/bios] Modern operating systems, such as Windows and Linux, use the BIOS interrupt calls only during the booting process.
[src:coreboot/bios] Before the operating system's first graphical screen is displayed, input and output are typically handled through BIOS.
[src:coreboot/bios] A boot menu such as the textual menu of Windows, which allows users to choose an operating system to boot, to boot into the safe mode, or to use the last known good configuration, is displayed through BIOS and receives keyboard input through BIOS.
[src:coreboot/bios] Many modern PCs can still boot and run legacy operating systems such as MS-DOS or DR-DOS that rely heavily on BIOS for their console and disk I/O, providing that the system has a BIOS, or a CSM-capable UEFI firmware.
[src:coreboot/bios] Intel processors have reprogrammable microcode since the P6 microarchitecture.
[src:coreboot/bios] AMD processors have reprogrammable microcode since the K7 microarchitecture.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS contains patches to the processor microcode that fix errors in the initial processor microcode; microcode is loaded into processor's SRAM so reprogramming is not persistent, thus loading of microcode updates is performed each time the system is powered up.
[src:coreboot/bios] Without reprogrammable microcode, an expensive processor swap would be required; for example, the Pentium FDIV bug became an expensive fiasco for Intel as it required a product recall because the original Pentium processor's defective microcode could not be reprogrammed.
[src:coreboot/bios] Operating systems can also update the microcode.
[src:coreboot/bios] Some BIOSes contain a software licensing description table (SLIC), a digital signature placed inside the BIOS by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM), for example Dell.
[src:coreboot/bios] The SLIC is inserted into the ACPI data table and contains no active code.
[src:coreboot/bios] Computer manufacturers that distribute OEM versions of Microsoft Windows and Microsoft application software can use the SLIC to authenticate licensing to the OEM Windows Installation disk and system recovery disc containing Windows software.
[src:coreboot/bios] Systems with a SLIC can be preactivated with an OEM product key, and they verify an XML formatted OEM certificate against the SLIC in the BIOS as a means of self-activating (see System Locked Preinstallation, SLP).
[src:coreboot/bios] If a user performs a fresh install of Windows, they will need to have possession of both the OEM key (either SLP or COA) and the digital certificate for their SLIC in order to bypass activation.
[src:coreboot/bios] This can be achieved if the user performs a restore using a pre-customised image provided by the OEM.
[src:coreboot/bios] Power users can copy the necessary certificate files from the OEM image, decode the SLP product key, then perform SLP activation manually.
[src:coreboot/bios] Some BIOS implementations allow overclocking, an action in which the CPU is adjusted to a higher clock rate than its manufacturer rating for guaranteed capability.
[src:coreboot/bios] Overclocking may, however, seriously compromise system reliability in insufficiently cooled computers and generally shorten component lifespan.
[src:coreboot/bios] Overclocking, when incorrectly performed, may also cause components to overheat so quickly that they mechanically destroy themselves.
[src:coreboot/bios] Some older operating systems, for example MS-DOS, rely on the BIOS to carry out most input/output tasks within the PC.
[src:coreboot/bios] Calling real mode BIOS services directly is inefficient for protected mode (and long mode) operating systems.
[src:coreboot/bios] BIOS interrupt calls are not used by modern multitasking operating systems after they initially load.
[src:coreboot/bios] In the 1990s, BIOS provided some protected mode interfaces for Microsoft Windows and Unix-like operating systems, such as Advanced Power Management (APM), Plug and Play BIOS, Desktop Management Interface (DMI), VESA BIOS Extensions (VBE), e820 and MultiProcessor Specification (MPS).
[src:coreboot/bios] Starting from the year 2000, most BIOSes provide ACPI, SMBIOS, VBE and e820 interfaces for modern operating systems.
[src:coreboot/bios] After operating systems load, the System Management Mode code is still running in SMRAM.
[src:coreboot/bios] Since 2010, BIOS technology is in a transitional process toward UEFI.
[src:coreboot/bios] Historically, the BIOS in the IBM PC and XT had no built-in user interface.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS versions in earlier PCs (XT-class) were not software configurable; instead, users set the options via DIP switches on the motherboard.
[src:coreboot/bios] Later computers, including most IBM-compatibles with 80286 CPUs, had a battery-backed nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS RAM chip) that held BIOS settings.
[src:coreboot/bios] These settings, such as video-adapter type, memory size, and hard-disk parameters, could only be configured by running a configuration program from a disk, not built into the ROM.
[src:coreboot/bios] A special "reference diskette" was inserted in an IBM AT to configure settings such as memory size.
[src:coreboot/bios] Early BIOS versions did not have passwords or boot-device selection options.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS was hard-coded to boot from the first floppy drive, or, if that failed, the first hard disk.
[src:coreboot/bios] Access control in early AT-class machines was by a physical keylock switch (which was not hard to defeat if the computer case could be opened).
[src:coreboot/bios] Anyone who could switch on the computer could boot it.
[src:coreboot/bios] Later, 386-class computers started integrating the BIOS setup utility in the ROM itself, alongside the BIOS code; these computers usually boot into the BIOS setup utility if a certain key or key combination is pressed, otherwise the BIOS POST and boot process are executed.
[src:coreboot/bios] A modern BIOS setup utility has a text user interface (TUI) or graphical user interface (GUI) accessed by pressing a certain key on the keyboard when the PC starts.
[src:coreboot/bios] Usually, the key is advertised for short time during the early startup, for example "Press DEL to enter Setup".
[src:coreboot/bios] The actual key depends on specific hardware.
[src:coreboot/bios] The settings key is most often Delete (Acer, ASRock, Asus PC, ECS, Gigabyte, MSI, Zotac) and F2 (Asus motherboard, Dell, Lenovo laptop, Origin PC, Samsung, Toshiba), but it can also be F1 (Lenovo desktop) and F10 (HP).
[src:coreboot/bios] A modern BIOS setup screen often features a **PC Health Status** or a **Hardware Monitoring** tab, which directly interfaces with a Hardware Monitor chip of the mainboard.
[src:coreboot/bios] This makes it possible to monitor CPU and chassis temperature, the voltage provided by the power supply unit, as well as monitor and control the speed of the fans connected to the motherboard.
[src:coreboot/bios] Some operating systems, like NetBSD with envsys and OpenBSD with sysctl hw.sensors, feature integrated interfacing with hardware monitors.
[src:coreboot/bios] However, in some circumstances, the BIOS also provides the underlying information about hardware monitoring through ACPI, in which case, the operating system may be using ACPI to perform hardware monitoring.
[src:coreboot/bios] In modern PCs the BIOS is stored in rewritable EEPROM or NOR flash memory, allowing the contents to be replaced and modified.
[src:coreboot/bios] This rewriting of the contents is sometimes termed *flashing.* It can be done by a special program, usually provided by the system's manufacturer, or at POST, with a BIOS image in a hard drive or USB flash drive.
[src:coreboot/bios] A file containing such contents is sometimes termed "a BIOS image".
[src:coreboot/bios] A BIOS might be reflashed in order to upgrade to a newer version to fix bugs or provide improved performance or to support newer hardware.
[src:coreboot/bios] Some computers also support updating the BIOS via an update floppy disk or a special partition on the hard drive.
[src:coreboot/bios] The original IBM PC BIOS (and cassette BASIC) was stored on mask-programmed read-only memory (ROM) chips in sockets on the motherboard.
[src:coreboot/bios] ROMs could be replaced, but not altered, by users.
[src:coreboot/bios] To allow for updates, many compatible computers used re-programmable BIOS memory devices such as EPROM, EEPROM and later flash memory (usually NOR flash) devices.
[src:coreboot/bios] According to Robert Braver, the president of the BIOS manufacturer Micro Firmware, **Flash BIOS** chips became common around 1995 because the electrically erasable PROM (EEPROM) chips are cheaper and easier to program than standard ultraviolet erasable PROM (EPROM) chips.
[src:coreboot/bios] Flash chips are programmed (and re-programmed) in-circuit, while EPROM chips need to be removed from the motherboard for re-programming.
[src:coreboot/bios] BIOS versions are upgraded to take advantage of newer versions of hardware and to correct bugs in previous revisions of BIOSes.
[src:coreboot/bios] Beginning with the IBM AT, PCs supported a hardware clock settable through BIOS.
[src:coreboot/bios] It had a century bit which allowed for manually changing the century when the year 2000 happened.
[src:coreboot/bios] Most BIOS revisions created in 1995 and nearly all BIOS revisions in 1997 supported the year 2000 by setting the century bit automatically when the clock rolled past midnight, 31 December 1999.
[src:coreboot/bios] The first flash chips were attached to the ISA bus.
[src:coreboot/bios] Starting in 1998, the BIOS flash moved to the LPC bus, following a new standard implementation known as "firmware hub" (FWH).
[src:coreboot/bios] In 2005, the BIOS flash memory moved to the SPI bus.
[src:coreboot/bios] The size of the BIOS, and the capacity of the ROM, EEPROM, or other media it may be stored on, has increased over time as new features have been added to the code; BIOS versions now exist with sizes up to 32 megabytes.
[src:coreboot/bios] For contrast, the original IBM PC BIOS was contained in an 8 KB mask ROM.
[src:coreboot/bios] Some modern motherboards are including even bigger NAND flash memory ICs on board which are capable of storing whole compact operating systems, such as some Linux distributions.
[src:coreboot/bios] For example, some ASUS notebooks included Splashtop OS embedded into their NAND flash memory ICs.
[src:coreboot/bios] However, the idea of including an operating system along with BIOS in the ROM of a PC is not new; in the 1980s, Microsoft offered a ROM option for MS-DOS, and it was included in the ROMs of some PC clones such as the Tandy 1000 HX.
[src:coreboot/bios] Another type of firmware chip was found on the IBM PC AT and early compatibles.
[src:coreboot/bios] In the AT, the keyboard interface was controlled by a microcontroller with its own programmable memory.
[src:coreboot/bios] On the IBM AT, that was a 40-pin socketed device, while some manufacturers used an EPROM version of this chip which resembled an EPROM.
[src:coreboot/bios] This controller was also assigned the A20 gate function to manage memory above the one-megabyte range; occasionally an upgrade of this "keyboard BIOS" was necessary to take advantage of software that could use upper memory.
[src:coreboot/bios] The BIOS may contain components such as the Memory Reference Code (MRC), which is responsible for the memory initialization (e.g.
[src:coreboot/bios] Modern BIOS includes Intel Management Engine or AMD Platform Security Processor firmware.
[src:coreboot/bios] IBM published full listings of the BIOSes for its original PC, PC XT, PC AT, and other contemporary PC models, in an appendix of the *IBM PC Technical Reference Manual* for each machine type.
[src:coreboot/bios] A benefit of the publication of the BIOS listings is that users could see exactly what the BIOS does and how it does it.
[src:coreboot/bios] However, those BIOSes were still copyright by IBM, so they could not be used by other manufacturers.
[src:coreboot/bios] In March 1983, Compaq released its Compaq Portable, which included a clean-room engineered BIOS.
[src:coreboot/bios] This made Compaq became the first company that cloned an IBM PC successfully.
[src:coreboot/bios] However, Compaq did not offer their BIOS to other computer manufacturers.
[src:coreboot/bios] In May 1984, Phoenix Software Associates released its first ROM-BIOS.
[src:coreboot/bios] This BIOS enabled OEMs to build essentially fully compatible clones without having to reverse-engineer the IBM PC BIOS themselves, as Compaq had done for the Portable; it also helped fuel the growth in the PC-compatibles industry and sales of non-IBM versions of DOS.
[src:coreboot/bios] The first American Megatrends (AMI) BIOS was released in 1986.
[src:coreboot/bios] New standards grafted onto the BIOS are usually without complete public documentation or any BIOS listings.
[src:coreboot/bios] As a result, it is not as easy to learn the intimate details about the many non-IBM additions to BIOS as about the core BIOS services.
[src:coreboot/bios] Many PC motherboard suppliers licensed the BIOS "core" and toolkit from a commercial third party, known as an "independent BIOS vendor" or IBV.
[src:coreboot/bios] The motherboard manufacturer then customized this BIOS to suit its own hardware.
[src:coreboot/bios] For this reason, updated BIOSes are normally obtained directly from the motherboard manufacturer.
[src:coreboot/bios] Major IBVs included American Megatrends (AMI), Insyde Software, Phoenix Technologies, and Byosoft.
[src:coreboot/bios] Microid Research and Award Software were acquired by Phoenix Technologies in 1998; Phoenix later phased out the Award brand name (although Award Software is still credited in AwardBIOS versions until 2001–2002, and AWRDACPI is still credited in Phoenix UEFI firmwares until late 2012).
[src:coreboot/bios] General Software, which was also acquired by Phoenix in 2007, sold BIOS for embedded systems based on Intel processors.
[src:coreboot/bios] SeaBIOS is an open-source BIOS implementation.
[src:coreboot/bios] The open-source community increased their effort to develop a replacement for proprietary BIOSes and their future incarnations with open-sourced counterparts.
[src:coreboot/bios] Open Firmware was an early attempt to make an open specification for boot firmware.
[src:coreboot/bios] It was initially endorsed by IEEE in its *IEEE 1275-1994* standard but was withdrawn in 2005.
[src:coreboot/bios] Later examples include the OpenBIOS, coreboot and libreboot projects.
[src:coreboot/bios] AMD provided product specifications for some chipsets using coreboot, and Google is sponsoring the project.
[src:coreboot/bios] Motherboard manufacturer Tyan offers coreboot next to the standard BIOS with their Opteron line of motherboards.
[src:coreboot/bios] EEPROM and flash memory chips are advantageous because they can be easily updated by the user; it is customary for hardware manufacturers to issue BIOS updates to upgrade their products, improve compatibility and remove bugs.
[src:coreboot/bios] However, this advantage had the risk that an improperly executed or aborted BIOS update could render the computer or device unusable.
[src:coreboot/bios] To avoid these situations, more recent BIOSes use a "boot block"; a portion of the BIOS which runs first and must be updated separately.
[src:coreboot/bios] This code verifies if the rest of the BIOS is intact (using hash checksums or other methods) before transferring control to it.
[src:coreboot/bios] If the boot block detects any corruption in the main BIOS, it will typically warn the user that a recovery process must be initiated by booting from removable media (floppy, CD or USB flash drive) so the user can try flashing the BIOS again.
[src:coreboot/bios] Some motherboards have a *backup* BIOS (sometimes referred as DualBIOS) to recover from BIOS corruptions, and they use a special PLC to do BIOS recovery from BIOS corruptions.
[src:coreboot/bios] There are at least five known viruses that attack the BIOS, two of which were for demonstration purposes.
[src:coreboot/bios] The first one found in the wild was *Mebromi*, targeting Chinese users.
[src:coreboot/bios] The first BIOS virus was BIOS Meningitis, which instead of erasing BIOS chips it infected them.
[src:coreboot/bios] BIOS Meningitis was relatively harmless, compared to a virus like CIH.
[src:coreboot/bios] The second BIOS virus was CIH, also known as the "Chernobyl Virus", which was able to erase flash ROM BIOS content on compatible chipsets.
[src:coreboot/bios] CIH appeared in mid-1998 and became active in April 1999.
[src:coreboot/bios] Often, infected computers could no longer boot, and people had to remove the flash ROM IC from the motherboard and reprogram it.
[src:coreboot/bios] CIH targeted the then-widespread Intel i430TX motherboard chipset and took advantage of the fact that the Windows 9x operating systems, also widespread at the time, allowed direct hardware access to all programs.
[src:coreboot/bios] Modern systems are not vulnerable to CIH because of a variety of chipsets being used which are incompatible with the Intel i430TX chipset, and also other flash ROM IC types.
[src:coreboot/bios] There is also extra protection from accidental BIOS rewrites in the form of boot blocks which are protected from accidental overwrite or dual BIOS equipped systems which may, in the event of a crash, use a backup BIOS.
[src:coreboot/bios] Also, all modern operating systems such as FreeBSD, Linux, macOS, Windows NT-based Windows OS like Windows 2000, Windows XP and newer, do not allow user-mode programs to have direct hardware access using a hardware abstraction layer.
[src:coreboot/bios] As a result, as of 2008, CIH has become essentially harmless, at worst causing annoyance by infecting executable files and triggering antivirus software.
[src:coreboot/bios] Other BIOS viruses remain possible, however; since most Windows home users without Windows Vista/7's UAC run all applications with administrative privileges, a modern CIH-like virus could in principle still gain access to hardware without first using an exploit.
[src:coreboot/bios] The operating system OpenBSD prevents all users from having this access and the grsecurity patch for the Linux kernel also prevents this direct hardware access by default, the difference being an attacker requiring a much more difficult kernel level exploit or reboot of the machine.
[src:coreboot/bios] The third BIOS virus was a technique presented by John Heasman, principal security consultant for UK-based Next-Generation Security Software.
[src:coreboot/bios] In 2006, at the Black Hat Security Conference, he showed how to elevate privileges and read physical memory, using malicious procedures that replaced normal ACPI functions stored in flash memory.
[src:coreboot/bios] The fourth BIOS virus was a technique called "Persistent BIOS infection." It appeared in 2009 at the CanSecWest Security Conference in Vancouver, and at the SyScan Security Conference in Singapore.
[src:coreboot/bios] Researchers Anibal Sacco and Alfredo Ortega, from Core Security Technologies, demonstrated how to insert malicious code into the decompression routines in the BIOS, allowing for nearly full control of the PC at start-up, even before the operating system is booted.
[src:coreboot/bios] The proof-of-concept does not exploit a flaw in the BIOS implementation, but only involves the normal BIOS flashing procedures.
[src:coreboot/bios] Thus, it requires physical access to the machine, or for the user to be root.
[src:coreboot/bios] Despite these requirements, Ortega underlined the profound implications of his and Sacco's discovery: "We can patch a driver to drop a fully working rootkit.
[src:coreboot/bios] Mebromi is a trojan which targets computers with AwardBIOS, Microsoft Windows, and antivirus software from two Chinese companies: Rising Antivirus and Jiangmin KV Antivirus.
[src:coreboot/bios] Mebromi installs a rootkit which infects the Master boot record.
[src:coreboot/bios] In a December 2013 interview with *60 Minutes*, Deborah Plunkett, Information Assurance Director for the US National Security Agency claimed the NSA had uncovered and thwarted a possible BIOS attack by a foreign nation state, targeting the US financial system.
[src:coreboot/bios] The program cited anonymous sources alleging it was a Chinese plot.
[src:coreboot/bios] However follow-up articles in *The Guardian,* *The Atlantic,* *Wired* and *The Register* refuted the NSA's claims.
[src:coreboot/bios] Newer Intel platforms have Intel Boot Guard (IBG) technology enabled, this technology will check the BIOS digital signature at startup, and the IBG public key is fused into the PCH.
[src:coreboot/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) supplements the BIOS in many new machines.
[src:coreboot/bios] Initially written for the Intel Itanium architecture, UEFI is now available for x86 and Arm platforms; the specification development is driven by the Unified EFI Forum, an industry special interest group.
[src:coreboot/bios] EFI booting has been supported in only Microsoft Windows versions supporting GPT, the Linux kernel 2.6.1 and later, and macOS on Intel-based Macs.
[src:coreboot/bios] As of 2014, new PC hardware predominantly ships with UEFI firmware.
[src:coreboot/bios] The architecture of the rootkit safeguard can also prevent the system from running the user's own software changes, which makes UEFI controversial as a legacy BIOS replacement in the open hardware community.
[src:coreboot/bios] UEFI is required for devices shipping with Windows 8 and above.
[src:coreboot/bios] Likewise, Windows 11 requires UEFI to boot, with the exception of IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11.
[src:coreboot/bios] After the popularity of UEFI in 2010s, the older BIOS that supported BIOS interrupt calls was renamed to "legacy BIOS".
[src:coreboot/bios] Other alternatives to the functionality of the "Legacy BIOS" in the x86 world include coreboot and libreboot.
[src:coreboot/bios] Some servers and workstations use a platform-independent Open Firmware (IEEE-1275) based on the Forth programming language; it is included with Sun's SPARC computers, IBM's RS/6000 line, and other PowerPC systems such as the CHRP motherboards, along with the x86-based OLPC XO-1.
[src:coreboot/bios] As of at least 2015, Apple has removed legacy BIOS support from the UEFI monitor in Intel-based Macs.
[src:coreboot/bios] As such, the BIOS utility no longer supports the legacy option, and prints "Legacy mode not supported on this system".
[src:coreboot/bios] In 2017, Intel announced that it would remove legacy BIOS support by 2020.
[src:coreboot/bios] Since 2019, new Intel platform OEM PCs no longer support the legacy option.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Because coreboot performs low‑level hardware initialization, it must be ported to each supported chipset and motherboard model; consequently, availability is limited to platforms for which support has been implemented.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] One of the well‑known variants of coreboot is Libreboot, a software distribution that focuses on removing proprietary binary blobs from the firmware stack.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] The coreboot project began with the goal of creating a BIOS that boots quickly and handles errors intelligently.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] It is distributed under the terms of the GNU General Public License version 2 (GPLv2).
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Main contributors include LANL, SiS, AMD, Coresystems and Linux Networx, Inc, as well as motherboard vendors MSI, Gigabyte and Tyan, which offer coreboot alongside their standard BIOS or provide specifications of the hardware interfaces for some of their motherboards.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Google partly sponsors the coreboot project.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] CME Group, a financial public company, began supporting the coreboot project in 2009.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Other than the first three models, all Chromebooks run coreboot.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Code from Das U-Boot has been assimilated to enable support for processors based on the ARM instruction set.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] In June 2019, coreboot began to use the NSA software Ghidra for its reverse engineering efforts on firmware-specific problems following the release of the suite as free and open source software.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] coreboot supports multiple CPU architectures, including IA-32, x86-64, ARM, ARM64, MIPS and RISC-V.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Support covers a variety of system-on-a-chip (SoC) platforms as well; early development focused on AMD Geode processors (notably those used in the OLPC project).
[src:coreboot/coreboot] From that initial development on AMD Geode based platforms, coreboot support has been extended onto many AMD processors and chipsets.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] The processor list includes Family 0Fh and 10h (K8 core), and recently Family 14h (Bobcat core, Fusion APU). coreboot support also extends to AMD chipsets: RS690, RS7xx, SB600, and SB8xx.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] In AMD Generic Encapsulated Software Architecture (AGESA)‍—‌a bootstrap protocol by which system devices on AMD64 mainboards are initialized‍—‌was open sourced in early 2011, aiming to provide required functionality for coreboot system initialization on AMD64 hardware.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] However, as of 2014 such releases never became the basis for future development by AMD, and were subsequently halted.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] The Libreboot T400 and X200 (rebranded ThinkPad T400 and X200, respectively, available from Minifree, previously known as Gluglug).
[src:coreboot/coreboot] StarLabs Systems use coreboot firmware, as an alternative.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] processor on the car computer, and adopted coreboot as the bootloader.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Booting other kernels directly is also possible, such as a Plan 9 kernel.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Instead of loading a kernel directly, coreboot can pass control to a dedicated boot loader, such as a coreboot-capable version of GNU GRUB 2.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Coreboot is primarily implemented in C, with a small amount of assembly code.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Choosing C as the primary programming language facilitates code audits when compared to contemporary PC BIOS that was generally written in assembly, which results in improved security.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] There is build and runtime support to write parts of coreboot in Ada to further raise the security bar, but it is currently only sporadically used.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] The source code is released under the GNU GPL version 2 license.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Coreboot performs the absolute minimal amount of hardware initialization and then passes control to the operating system.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] As a result, there is no coreboot code running once the operating system has taken control.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] A feature of coreboot is that the x86 version runs in 32-bit mode after executing only ten instructions (almost all other x86 BIOSes run exclusively in 16-bit mode).
[src:coreboot/coreboot] This is similar to the modern UEFI firmware, which is used on newer PC hardware.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] The most difficult hardware that coreboot initializes is the DRAM controllers and DRAM.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] In some cases, technical documentation on this subject is NDA restricted or unavailable.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] RAM initialization is particularly difficult because before the RAM is initialized it cannot be used.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Therefore, to initialize DRAM controllers and DRAM, the initialization code may have only the CPU's general purpose registers or Cache-as-RAM as temporary storage.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] romcc, a C compiler that uses registers instead of RAM, eases the task.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Using romcc, it is relatively easy to make SMBus accesses to the SPD ROMs of the DRAM DIMMs, that allows the RAM to be used.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] With newer x86 processors, the processor cache can be used as RAM until DRAM is initialized.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] The processor cache has to be initialized into Cache-as-RAM mode as well, but this needs fewer instructions than initializing DRAM.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Also, the Cache-as-RAM mode initialization is specific to CPU architectures, thus more generic than DRAM initialization, which is specific to each chipset and mainboard.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] For most modern x86 platforms, closed source binary-only components provided by the vendor are used for DRAM setup.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] For Intel systems, FSP-M is required, while AMD has no current support.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Binary AGESA is currently used for proprietary UEFI firmware on AMD systems, and this model is expected to carry over to any future AMD-related coreboot support.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Developers use a variety of hardware and software debugging tools when working on coreboot.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] These include in‑circuit emulators, JTAG probes (for example the Sage SmartProbe), and BIOS/firmware emulators.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Code may be tested on emulators or downloaded to target hardware rather than being immediately flashed to a BIOS device. being an example.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Code can be built on, or downloaded to, BIOS emulators rather than flashing the BIOS device.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] coreboot loads a payload after hardware initialization.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] Payloads may be written with the libpayload helper library or be independent projects.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] One physical meeting is the European Coreboot Conference which was organized in October 2017 and lasted for three days.
[src:coreboot/coreboot] coreboot has a number of variants from its original code base each with slightly different objectives:.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The historical precursor to FOSS was the hobbyist and academic public domain software ecosystem of the 1960s to 1980s.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Free and open-source operating systems such as Linux distributions and descendants of BSD are widely used, powering millions of servers, desktops, smartphones, and other devices.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Free-software licenses and open-source licenses have been adopted by many software packages.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Reasons for using FOSS include decreased software costs, increased security against malware, stability, privacy, opportunities for educational usage, and giving users more control over their own hardware.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The free software movement and the open-source software movement are online social movements behind widespread production, adoption and promotion of FOSS, with the former preferring to use the equivalent term *free/libre and open-source software*.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] FOSS is supported by a loosely associated movement of multiple organizations, foundations, communities and individuals who share basic philosophical perspectives and collaborate practically, but may diverge in detail questions.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Although there is an almost complete overlap between free-software licenses and open-source-software licenses, there is a strong philosophical disagreement between the advocates of these two positions.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Proponents of permissive and copyleft licenses disagree on whether software freedom should be viewed as a negative or positive liberty.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Due to their restrictions on distribution, not everyone considers copyleft licenses to be free.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Conversely, a permissive license may provide an incentive to create non-free software by reducing the cost of developing restricted software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Since this is incompatible with the spirit of software freedom, many people consider permissive licenses to be less free than copyleft licenses.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Richard Stallman's *The Free Software Definition*, adopted by the FSF, defines free software as a matter of liberty, not price, and that which upholds the Four Essential Freedoms.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The earliest known publication of this definition of his free software definition was in the February 1986 edition of the FSF's now-discontinued GNU's Bulletin publication.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The canonical source for the document is in the philosophy section of the GNU Project website.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] As of August 2017, it is published in 40 languages.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] To meet the definition of *free software*, the FSF requires the software's licensing respect the civil liberties / human rights of what the FSF calls the software user's "Four Essential Freedoms".
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] In the early decades of computing, particularly from the 1950s through the 1970s, software development was largely collaborative.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Programs were commonly shared in source code form among academics, researchers, and corporate developers.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Most companies at the time made their revenue from hardware sales, and software—including source code—was distributed freely alongside it, often as public-domain software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] By the late 1960s and 1970s, a distinct software industry began to emerge.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Companies started selling software as a separate product, leading to the use of restrictive licenses and technical measures—such as distributing only binary executables—to limit user access and control.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] This shift was driven by growing competition and the U.S. government's antitrust scrutiny of bundled software, exemplified by the 1969 antitrust case *United States v.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] A key turning point came in 1980 when U.S. copyright law was formally extended to cover computer software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] This enabled companies like IBM to further enforce closed-source distribution models.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] In 1983, IBM introduced its "object code only" policy, ceasing the distribution of source code for its system software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] In response to the growing restrictions on software, Richard Stallman launched the GNU Project in 1983 at MIT.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] His goal was to develop a complete Free software operating system and restore user freedom.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The Free Software Foundation (FSF) was established in 1985 to support this mission.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Stallman's *GNU Manifesto* and the Four Essential Freedoms outlined the movement's ethical stance, emphasizing user control over software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The release of the Linux kernel by Linus Torvalds in 1991, and its relicense under the GNU General Public License (GPL) in 1992, marked a major step toward a fully Free operating system.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Other Free software projects like FreeBSD, NetBSD, and OpenBSD also gained traction following the resolution of the *USL v.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] In 1997, Eric Raymond's essay *The Cathedral and the Bazaar* explored the development model of Free software, influencing Netscape's decision in 1998 to release the source code for its browser suite.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] This code base became Mozilla Firefox and Thunderbird.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Despite initial resistance—such as Microsoft's 2001 claim that "Open-source is an intellectual property destroyer"—FOSS eventually gained widespread acceptance in the corporate world.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Companies like Red Hat proved that commercial success and Free software principles could coexist.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Users of FOSS benefit from the Four Essential Freedoms to make unrestricted use of, and to study, copy, modify, and redistribute such software with or without modification.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Manufacturers of proprietary, closed-source software are sometimes pressured to building in backdoors or other covert, undesired features into their software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Instead of having to trust software vendors, users of FOSS can inspect and verify the source code themselves and can put trust on a community of volunteers and users.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] As proprietary code is typically hidden from public view, only the vendors themselves and hackers may be aware of any vulnerabilities in them while FOSS involves as many people as possible for exposing bugs quickly.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] FOSS is often free of charge although donations are often encouraged.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] This also allows users to better test and compare software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] FOSS allows for better collaboration among various parties and individuals with the goal of developing the most efficient software for its users or use-cases while proprietary software is typically meant to generate profits.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Furthermore, in many cases more organizations and individuals contribute to such projects than to proprietary software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] It has been shown that technical superiority is typically the primary reason why companies choose open source software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] According to Linus's law, the more people who can see and test a set of code, the more likely any flaws will be caught and fixed quickly.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] However, this does not guarantee a high level of participation.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Having a team of full-time professionals behind a commercial product can, in some cases, lead to more secure code than in a volunteer-driven FOSS project.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Furthermore, publicized source code might make it easier for hackers to find vulnerabilities in it and write exploits.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] This however assumes that such malicious hackers are more effective than white hat hackers which responsibly disclose or help fix the vulnerabilities, that no code leaks or exfiltrations occur and that reverse engineering of proprietary code is a hindrance of significance for malicious hackers.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Sometimes, FOSS is not compatible with proprietary hardware or specific software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] While FOSS can be superior to proprietary equivalents in terms of software features and stability, in many cases it has more unfixed bugs and missing features when compared to similar commercial software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] This varies per case, and usually depends on the level of interest in a particular project.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] However, unlike close-sourced software, improvements can be made by anyone who has the motivation, time and skill to do so.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] A common obstacle in FOSS development is the lack of access to some common official standards, due to costly royalties or required non-disclosure agreements (e.g., for the DVD-Video format).
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] There is often less certainty of FOSS projects gaining the required resources and participation for continued development than commercial software backed by companies.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] However, companies also often abolish projects for being unprofitable, yet large companies may rely on, and hence co-develop, open source software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] On the other hand, if the vendor of proprietary software ceases development, there are no alternatives; whereas with FOSS, any user who needs it still has the right, and the source-code, to continue to develop it themself, or pay a 3rd party to do so.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] As the FOSS operating system distributions of Linux has a lower market share of end users there are also fewer applications available.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] (ISS), regarding why they chose to switch from Windows to Linux on the ISS.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] In 2020, the European Commission adopted its *Open Source Strategy 2020-2023*, including encouraging sharing and reuse of software and publishing Commission's source code as key objectives.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Among concrete actions there is also to set up an Open Source Programme Office in 2020 and in 2022 it launched its own FOSS repository code.europa.eu.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] In 2021, the *Commission Decision on the open source licensing and reuse of Commission software (2021/C 495 I/01)* was adopted, under which, as a general principle, the European Commission may release software under EUPL or another FOSS license, if more appropriate.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] In May 2022, the *Expert group on the Interoperability of European Public Services* came published 27 recommendations to strengthen the interoperability of public administrations across the EU.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] These recommendations are to be taken into account later in the same year in Commission's proposal of the *"Interoperable Europe Act"*.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Open-source software development (OSSD) is the process by which open-source software is developed.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The software's source code is publicly available to be used, modified, and enhanced.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Notable examples of open-source software products are Mozilla Firefox, Android, and VLC media player.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The development process is typically different from traditional methods such as Waterfall.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Instead favoring early releases and community involvement.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Agile development strategies are most often employed OSSD, with are characterized by their iterative and incremental frameworks.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Open-source software developers will typically use methods such as E-mail, Wikis, web forums, and instant messaging services for communication, as individuals are not typically working in close proximity to one another.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Version control systems such as Git are utilized to make code collaboration easier.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The GNU General Public License (GPL) is one of the most widely used copyleft licenses in the free and open-source software (FOSS) community and was created by the Free Software Foundation (FSF).
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Version 2 (GPLv2), published in 1991, played a central role in protecting the freedom of software to be run, studied, modified, and shared by users.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] However, as technology and legal landscapes evolved, particularly with the rise of Digital Rights Management (DRM) and software patents, some developers and legal experts argued that GPLv2 did not adequately protect user freedoms in newer contexts.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] This led to the development of GPLv3, which sought to address these concerns.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] While copyright is the primary legal mechanism that FOSS authors use to ensure license compliance for their software, other mechanisms such as legislation, patents, and trademarks have implications as well.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] In response to legal issues with patents and the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA), the Free Software Foundation released version 3 of its GNU General Public License (GNU GPLv3) in 2007 that explicitly addressed the DMCA and patent rights.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] One of the key issues GPLv3 aimed to address was a practice known as Tivoization, named after the company TiVo, which used GPL-covered software but implemented hardware restrictions that prevented users from running modified versions of the software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] This was seen by the Free Software Foundation (FSF) as a direct violation of software freedom, prompting GPLv3 to include language explicitly forbidding such restrictions.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Additionally, GPLv3 introduced clauses to protect users against aggressive enforcement of software patents and reinforced the idea that users should retain control over the software they use.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] After the development of the GNU GPLv3 in 2007, the FSF (as the copyright holder of many pieces of the GNU system) updated many of the GNU programs' licenses from GPLv2 to GPLv3.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] On the other hand, the adoption of the new GPL version was heavily discussed in the FOSS ecosystem, several projects decided against upgrading to GPLv3.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] For instance the Linux kernel, the BusyBox project, AdvFS, Blender, and the VLC media player decided against adopting the GPLv3.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Apple, a user of GCC and a heavy user of both DRM and patents, switched the compiler in its Xcode IDE from GCC to Clang, which is another FOSS compiler but is under a permissive license.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] LWN speculated that Apple was motivated partly by a desire to avoid GPLv3.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The Samba project also switched to GPLv3, so Apple replaced Samba in their software suite by a closed-source, proprietary software alternative.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The controversy with GPLv3 mirrored a more general philosophical split in the open source community: whether people should hold licenses that aggressively defend user freedoms (as with copyleft) or take a more permissive, collaborative yet ambiguous approach.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Supporters applauded GPLv3 for fortifying protections against restrictions imposed by hardware and patent threats, while critics felt it created legal and ideological barriers that complicated its development and made it less appealing to adopt.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The fallout helped to raise the acceptance of permissive licenses like the MIT and Apache licenses, especially by commercial software developers.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Leemhuis criticizes the priorities of skilled developers who − instead of fixing issues in already popular open-source applications and desktop environments − create new, mostly redundant software to gain fame and fortune.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] He also criticizes notebook manufacturers for optimizing their own products only privately or creating workarounds instead of helping fix the actual causes of the many issues with Linux on notebooks such as the unnecessary power consumption.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Mergers have affected major open-source software.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Sun Microsystems (Sun) acquired MySQL AB, owner of the popular open-source MySQL database, in 2008.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Oracle in turn purchased Sun in January 2010, acquiring their copyrights, patents, and trademarks.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Thus, Oracle became the owner of both the most popular proprietary database and the most popular open-source database.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Oracle's attempts to commercialize the open-source MySQL database have raised concerns in the FOSS community.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Partly in response to uncertainty about the future of MySQL, the FOSS community forked the project into new database systems outside of Oracle's control.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] These include MariaDB, Percona, and Drizzle.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] All of these have distinct names; they are distinct projects and cannot use the trademarked name MySQL.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] In August 2010, Oracle sued Google, claiming that its use of Java in Android infringed on Oracle's copyrights and patents.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] In May 2012, the trial judge determined that Google did not infringe on Oracle's patents and ruled that the structure of the Java APIs used by Google was not copyrightable.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] The jury found that Google infringed a small number of copied files, but the parties stipulated that Google would pay no damages.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Oracle appealed to the Federal Circuit, and Google filed a cross-appeal on the literal copying claim.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] By defying ownership regulations in the construction and use of information—a key area of contemporary growth—the Free/Open Source Software (FOSS) movement counters neoliberalism and privatization in general.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] By realizing the historical potential of an "economy of abundance" for the new digital world, FOSS may lay down a plan for political resistance or show the way towards a potential transformation of capitalism.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] According to Yochai Benkler, Jack N. and Lillian R.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] Berkman Professor for Entrepreneurial Legal Studies at Harvard Law School, free software is the most visible part of a new economy of commons-based peer production of information, knowledge, and culture.
[src:coreboot/free-and-open-source-software] As examples, he cites a variety of FOSS projects, including both free software and open-source.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] Libreboot is established as a distribution of coreboot, but with some proprietary binary blobs removed from coreboot.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] Libreboot makes coreboot easy to use by automating the build and installation processes.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] On some devices, Libreboot developers have reverse engineered the firmware from Intel and created a utility to create a free firmware that meets the specifications from Intel.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] Hardware support includes but is not limited to the ASUS KGPE-D16, ThinkPad T400, X60 and X200.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] Libreboot is officially endorsed by the upstream coreboot project.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] Internal flashing is possible, but it's recommended to have a working external flashing setup that could be used to recover from mistakes when flashing internally.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] It is strongly advised not to use the CH341A programmer, as it can easily damage BIOS chips.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] For safety, use the Raspberry Pi Pico with a SOIC clip.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] Probably the most famous feature of Libreboot, and one that also highly impacts the security and possibly the privacy of the user, is that on most machines, Libreboot disables the Intel Management Engine by default.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] On older machines (before ME version 6.0), the Intel ME code could be entirely removed from the flash memory, thus completely disabling the ME.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] This is the case on devices like the ThinkPad X200 or ThinkPad T400.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] On newer devices, the Intel ME is needed to boot the machine, because of this, the ME is not completely disabled, but rather put into a inactive or "disabled" state after the machine boots.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] The Libreboot project was started in December 2013 as a distribution of coreboot, which excludes non-free binary blobs.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] Coreboot began as LinuxBIOS in 1999 at Los Alamos National Labs (LANL), and was renamed "coreboot" in 2008.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] Libreboot has been endorsed by the Free Software Foundation, and was an official part of the GNU Project starting in May 2016.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] In January 2017, the project's maintainer Leah Rowe pulled Libreboot from the GNU Project, after a months-long dispute with the Free Software Foundation which oversees GNU.
[src:coreboot/libreboot] In 2015, Kyle Rankin stated in *Linux Journal* that Libreboot "greatly simplified and automated" the flashing process, "with a few caveats".
[src:coreboot/libreboot] In 2016, Bryan Cockfield stated in Hackaday that Libreboot installation was "harrowing" and "not as easy as you'd think".
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] In computing and telecommunications, the **payload** is the part of transmitted data that is the actual intended message.
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] Headers and metadata are sent only to enable payload delivery and are considered overhead.
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] In the context of a computer virus or worm, the payload is the portion of the malware which performs malicious action.
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] The term is borrowed from transportation, where *payload* refers to the part of the load that *pays* for transportation.
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] In computer networking, the data to be transmitted is the payload.
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] It is almost always encapsulated in some type of frame format, composed of framing bits and a frame check sequence.
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] Examples are Ethernet frames, Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) frames, Fibre Channel frames, and V.42 modem frames.
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] In computer programming, the most common usage of the term is in the context of message protocols, to differentiate the protocol overhead from the actual data.
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] The string *Hello, world!* is the payload of JSON message, while the rest is protocol overhead.
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] In computer security, the payload is the part of the private user text which could also contain malware such as worms or viruses which performs the malicious action; deleting data, sending spam or encrypting data.
[src:coreboot/payload-computing] In addition to the payload, such malware also typically has overhead code aimed at simply spreading itself, or avoiding detection.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] A **power-on self-test** (**POST**) is a process performed by firmware or software routines immediately after a computer or other digital electronic device is powered on.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] POST processes may set the initial state of the device and detect if any hardware components are non-functional.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The results of the POST may be displayed on a panel that is part of the device, output to an external device, or stored for future retrieval by a diagnostic tool.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In some computers, an indicator lamp or a speaker may be provided to show error codes as a sequence of flashes or beeps in the event that a computer display malfunctions.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] POST routines are part of a computer's **pre-boot sequence**.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] If they complete successfully, the bootstrap loader code is invoked to load an operating system.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In IBM PC compatible computers, the main duties of POST are handled by the BIOS or UEFI.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In IBM PC compatible computers, the main duties of POST are handled by the BIOS or UEFI, which may hand some of these duties to other programs designed to initialize very specific peripheral devices, notably for video and SCSI initialization.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] These other duty-specific programs are generally known collectively as option ROMs or individually as the video BIOS, SCSI BIOS, etc.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In earlier BIOSes, up to around the turn of the millennium, the POST would perform a thorough test of all devices, including a complete memory test.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] This design by IBM was modeled after their larger mainframe systems, which would perform a complete hardware test as part of their cold-start process.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] As the PC platform evolved into more of a commodity consumer device, the mainframe and minicomputer-inspired high-reliability features such as parity memory and the thorough memory test in every POST were dropped from most models.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The exponential growth of PC memory sizes, driven by the equally exponential drop in memory prices, was also a factor in this, as the duration of a memory test using a given CPU is directly proportional to the memory size.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The original IBM PC could be equipped with as little as 16 KB of RAM and typically had between 64 and 640 KB; depending on the amount of equipped memory, the computer's 4.77 MHz 8088 required between 5 seconds and 1.5 minutes to complete the POST and there was no way to skip it.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Beginning with the IBM XT, a memory count was displayed during POST instead of a blank screen.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] A modern PC with a bus rate of around 1 GHz and a 32-bit bus might be 2000x or even 5000x faster, but might have many more gigabytes of memory.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] With boot times more of a concern now than in the 1980s, the 30- to 60-second memory test adds undesirable delay for a benefit of confidence that is not perceived to be worth that cost by most users.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Most clone PC BIOSes allowed the user to skip the POST RAM check by pressing a key, and more modern machines (2000s and later) often performed no RAM test at all unless it was enabled via the BIOS setup.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In addition, modern DRAM is significantly more reliable than DRAM was in the 1980s.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] During the POST, the BIOS must integrate multiple competing, changing, and even mutually exclusive standards and initiatives for the matrix of hardware and operating systems the PC is expected to support, although at most only simple memory tests and the setup screen are displayed.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The functions above are served by the POST in all BIOS versions back to the very first.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In early BIOSes, POST did not organize or select boot devices; it simply identified floppy or hard disks, which the system would always try to boot in that order.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The BIOS begins its POST when the CPU is reset.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The first memory location the CPU tries to execute is known as the reset vector.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In the case of a hard reboot, the northbridge will direct a code fetch request to the BIOS located on the system flash memory.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] For a warm boot, the BIOS will be located in the proper place in RAM and the northbridge will direct the reset vector call to the RAM.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In earlier PC systems, before chipsets were standard, the BIOS ROM would be located at an address range that included the reset vector, and BIOS ran directly out of ROM.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] This is why the motherboard BIOS ROM is in segment F000 in the conventional memory map.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] During the POST flow of a contemporary BIOS, one of the first things a BIOS should do is determine the reason it is executing.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] For a cold boot, for example, it may need to execute all of its functionality.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] If, however, the system supports power-saving or quick-boot methods, the BIOS may be able to circumvent the standard POST device discovery and simply program the devices from a preloaded system device table.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] As part of the starting sequence the POST routines may display a prompt to the user for a key press to access built-in setup functions of the BIOS.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] This allows the user to set various options particular to the motherboard before the operating system is loaded.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] If no key is pressed, the POST will proceed on to the boot sequence required to load the installed operating system.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Many modern BIOS and UEFI implementations show a manufacturer's logo during POST and hide the classic text screens unless an error occurs.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The text screen can often be enabled in the BIOS settings by disabling the "Quiet Boot" option.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The original IBM BIOS made POST diagnostic information available by outputting a number to I/O port 0x80 (a screen display was not possible with some failure modes).
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Both progress indication and error codes were generated; in the case of a failure which did not generate a code, the code of the last successful operation was available to aid in diagnosing the problem.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Using a logic analyzer or a dedicated POST card‍—‌an interface card that shows port 0x80 output on a small display‍—‌a technician could determine the origin of the problem.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Once an operating system is running on the computer the code displayed by such a board may become meaningless, since some OSes, e.g.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Linux, use port 0x80 for I/O timing operations.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The actual numeric codes for the possible stages and error conditions differ from one BIOS supplier to another.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Codes for different BIOS versions from a single supplier may also vary, although many codes remain unchanged in different versions.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Later BIOSes used a sequence of beeps from the motherboard-attached PC speaker (if present and working) to signal error codes.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Some vendors developed proprietary variants or enhancements, such as MSI's D-Bracket.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] POST beep codes vary from manufacturer to manufacturer.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Information on numeric and beep codes is available from manufacturers of BIOSes and motherboards.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] There are websites which collect codes for many BIOSes.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Apple's Macintosh computers also perform a POST after a cold boot.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In the event of a fatal error, the Mac will not make its startup chime.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Macs made before 1987, upon failing the POST, crashed silently without playing any sound and froze, with a single hexadecimal string and a Sad Mac icon on the screen, if working.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Macs made after 1987 but before 1998, upon failing the POST, will immediately halt with a "death chime", which is a sound that varies by model; it can be a simple beep, a car crash sound, the sound of shattering glass, a short musical tone, or more.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] On the screen, if working, will be the Sad Mac icon, along with two hexadecimal strings, which can be used to identify the problem.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Some Macs made during that same time period do not use a death chime like Macs made before 1987, but retained the same format as those that used the death chimes, such as the presence of the Sad Mac icon and two hexadecimal strings on screen.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Old World Macs based on PCI architecture before 1998 don’t display a Sad Mac icon nor the hexadecimal strings on screen and only play the death chime.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] When Apple introduced the iMac in 1998, it was a radical departure from other Macs of the time.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The iMac began the production of New World Macs, as they are called; New World Macs, such as the iMac G3, Power Macintosh G3 (Blue & White), Power Mac G4 (PCI Graphics), PowerBook G3 (bronze keyboard), and PowerBook G3 (FireWire), load the Mac OS ROM from the hard drive.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In the event of an error that is not a fatal hardware error, they display the same screen as seen when holding ⌘ Command+⌥ Option+O+F at startup but with the error message instead of the "0 >" prompt.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The beep codes were revised in October 1999.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In addition, on some models, the power LED will flash in cadence.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] With the introduction of Intel-based Macs using UEFI, the startup tones were changed again.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] These tones are not present in Intel-based Macs equipped with a T2 security chip, as they handle the POST process differently from those without a T2 security chip.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The Mac transition to Apple silicon marked a radical change in the POST process in Macs.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Unlike most Intel-based Macs with UEFI, Apple silicon-based Macs use a boot ROM that loads the Low-Level Bootloader (LLB), similar to that of the firmware for the iPhone and iPad.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] No audible beep codes or tones are used to indicate hardware failures, similar to Intel-based Macs equipped with a T2 security chip.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In the event of an error that is not a fatal hardware error, an exclamation mark will be displayed on the screen or the device will go into Device Firmware Update (DFU) mode.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] In the event of a fatal hardware error, no audio or visual feedback is provided.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Disables and clears all DMA and interrupts.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Checks the general hardware configuration.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] If the screen remains a light gray color and the tests continue, the hardware is OK.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] If the system fails the ROM test, the screen display turns red and the system halts.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Almost all Amiga models present the same color sequence when turned on: black screen, dark gray, light gray color screens filling the entire monitor screen in a rapid sequence (Amigas usually take between 2 and 3 seconds to turn on and boot).
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] The keyboards of historical Amiga models are not proprietary as it happened in early computer ages, but more pragmatically it was based on international standard ANSI/ISO 8859-1.
[src:coreboot/power-on-self-test] Many embedded systems such as those in major appliances, avionics, communications, or medical equipment have built-in self-test routines that are automatically invoked at power-on.
